CenturyLink did it again —

CenturyLink left customers without Internet for 39 days—until Ars stepped in

After over a month with no fix, service restored hours after Ars contacted ISP.

Jon Brodkin - 2/29/2024, 8:34 AM

reader comments

70

When a severe winter storm hit Oregon on January 13, Nicholas Brown's CenturyLink fiber Internet service stopped working at his house in Portland.

The initial outage was understandable amid the widespread damage caused by the storm, but CenturyLink's response was poor. It took about 39 days for CenturyLink to restore broadband service to Brown and even longer to restore service to one of his neighbors. Those reconnections only happened after Ars Technica contacted the telco firm on the customers' behalf last week.

Brown had never experienced any lengthy outage in over four years of subscribing to CenturyLink, so he figured the telco firm would restore his broadband connection within a reasonable amount of time. "It had practically never gone down at all up to this point. I've been quite happy with it," he said.

While CenturyLink sent trucks to his street to reconnect most of his neighbors after the storm and Brown regularly contacted CenturyLink to plead for a fix, his Internet connection remained offline. Brown had also lost power, but the electricity service was reconnected within about 48 hours, while the broadband service remained offline for well over a month.

Fearing he had exhausted his options, Brown contacted Ars. We sent an email to CenturyLink's media department on February 21 to seek information on why the outage lasted so long.

Telco finally springs into action

Roughly four hours after we contacted the firm, a CenturyLink technician arrived at the Portland house Brown shares with his partner, Jolene Edwards. The technician was able to reconnect them that day.

"At 4:30 pm, a CenturyLink tech showed up unannounced," Brown told us. "No one was home at the time, but he said he would wait. I get the idea that he was told not to come back until it was fixed."

Brown's neighbor, Leonard Bentz, also lost Internet access on January 13 and remained offline for two days longer than Brown. The technician who arrived on February 21 didn't reconnect Bentz's house.

"My partner gently tried to egg him to go over there and fix them too, and he more or less said, 'That's not the ticket that I have,'" Brown said.

After getting Bentz's name and address, we contacted CenturyLink again on February 22 to notify them that he also needed to be reconnected. CenturyLink later confirmed to us that it restored his Internet service on February 23.

“They kept putting me off and putting me off”

Bentz told Ars that during the month-plus outage, he called CenturyLink several times. Customer service reps and a supervisor told him the company would send someone to fix his service, but "they kept putting me off and putting me off and putting me off," Bentz said.

On one of those calls, Bentz said that CenturyLink promised him seven free months of service in exchange for the long outage. Brown told us he received a refund for the entire length of his outage, plus a bit extra. He pays $65 a month for gigabit service.

Brown said he is "happy enough with the resolution," at least financially since he "got all the money for the non-service." But those 39 days without Internet service will remain a bad memory.

Unfortunately, Internet service providers like CenturyLink have a history of failing to fix problems until media coverage exposes their poor customer service. CenturyLink is officially called Lumen these days, but it still uses the CenturyLink brand name.

After fixing Brown's service in Portland, a CenturyLink spokesperson gave us the following statement:

It's frustrating to have your services down and for that we apologize. We've brought in additional resources to assist in restoring service that was knocked out due to severe storms and multiple cases of vandalism. Some services are back, and we are working diligently to completely restore everything. In fact, we have technicians there now. We appreciate our customers' patience and understanding, and we welcome calls from our customers to discuss their service.

Page:

Yes, CenturyLink has done this before

Brown's situation was almost exactly like one we wrote about in August 2023. In that case, which did not involve a storm, CenturyLink left 86-year-old Minnesota resident Helen Marie Plourde without home Internet and phone service for over a month. CenturyLink finally fixed Plourde's service one day after we emailed the ISP's public relations department.

In Plourde's case, she was buying telecom service through a local CenturyLink reseller named Velocity Telephone. Velocity told Ars at the time that it set up CenturyLink appointments for Plourde three times, but no CenturyLink technicians showed up for any of the appointments.

Plourde said she contacted CenturyLink directly five or six times and only reached a person once. "Even the tone of voice was like, 'Well, ma'am, it's too bad, but you'll just have to wait,'" she said at the time.

During the Oregon storm, a tree took out some aerial lines, and CenturyLink sent crews to reconnect them. "A couple of different times, they had contractors in bucket trucks out here re-stringing fiber, and every time I saw them, I thought, 'Oh man, we're going to be fixed.' But it never did fix it," Brown said.

Brown said he contacted CenturyLink about once a week during the outage, and the company kept giving him new dates for a service restoration. Those dates came and went without an explanation of why the broadband connection was still out.

Customer service frustrations

One technician visit was scheduled for January 22, nine days after Brown's outage began, but "the technician visit was auto-cancelled by them with no action on my part," he said.

"I've chatted and called multiple times with support personnel, who all repeat that they can see the ticket, they can see exactly how long our service has been down (to the minute), and that they have no influence over (or ability to put me in touch with anyone who can influence) that repair ticket for the other team," Brown told us. "I was told that the team is stretched really thin due to copper issues all around town."

Brown was able to get a technician to his house on February 5, and the technician informed them that their in-home equipment was fine and that the fiber drop connecting directly to the house was intact. The problem was somewhere else in the fiber network, but the technician apparently couldn't figure out where.

The technicians' "equipment measured a break in the connection" somewhere beyond the fiber drop to the house, Brown said. "The technician confirmed that he was not able to perform that fix; he would have to create a ticket with whatever team does have the ability to fix the fiber," he said.

Fiber “was never reconnected properly”

After that visit, "the ticket resolution date has continued to be pushed back multiple times, with no explanation or notice to me when it happens," Brown told us on February 20. "The current stated fix time is Friday, February 23 at this point, but no one can give me any assurance that it will not push again, and I just have to keep checking to make sure the date hasn't magically moved."

That was the status quo until we contacted CenturyLink on February 21. The technician who came that day identified where the problem was and got the fiber service working again.

While it's not clear exactly what happened, Brown said the technician's remarks indicated "that the contractors either missed something or screwed something up, and ours was never reconnected properly and it was never going to work until he noticed this."

To Brown, it sounded like the problems were at least partly due to "third-party contractors making up for the fact that they didn't have enough hands on deck." The technician, we were told, mentioned that contractors did "something funky at the poles" and that he had to install an adapter to get the house online again.

"Apparently some contractors had replaced all the downed fiber, but our connection was never correctly re-established and never was going to work without whatever he installed," Brown said. "So it would've been fixed if they hadn't contracted out the job to someone else and if the right hand knew at all what the left one was doing."

Page:

Phone hotspots and bar Wi-Fi came in handy

Brown and Edwards made do with cellular data throughout the outage, but it was a struggle. "I'm also unemployed at the moment, and my partner works from home. We've been getting by using our iPhones as hotspots, and we had to carefully sort of figure out what the data usage was going to look like for various and sundry different things," Brown said.

Brown got some of his Internet needs met at a nearby bar. He worked in software product management before getting laid off, and one job he applied to during the outage required him to set up a Kubernetes test lab.

"I effectively had to do that entire thing from the bar because I just didn't have enough bandwidth to download a couple of gigabytes of setup utilities and things," he said.

Finally getting back online was a relief. "It's been surreal to just open a laptop and, like, it works, because I've been carrying around my iPhone in one hand and a USB cable for tethering in the other," he said.

Comcast is an option, but unappealing

Brown likes to test out Linux and BSD distributions, but that hobby was mostly put on hold during the outage. Once the broadband was reconnected, "I literally downloaded a couple of ISOs of various distributions that I'm installing on my laptops now," he said.

Brown said he looked into Verizon's 5G Home Internet during the outage but that "Verizon said they don't serve my address for whatever reason, even though my Verizon cell phone gets 5G here."

Comcast also provides service in Brown's area, but he's reluctant to switch. It would be more expensive for similar download speeds, and Comcast's cable network doesn't provide the symmetrical upload and download speeds that fiber allows.

Comcast also hasn't previously extended lines to his house, Brown said. Comcast often charges thousands or even tens of thousands of dollars in upfront installation fees for homes not already on its network, depending on the distance to the closest line. Brown said he wouldn't be excited about paying more "to have the privilege of having everyone's least-favorite provider, even if they would come install it quickly."

For now, Brown said he's just happy to have a working broadband connection. "It's amazing how much convenience there is in it just working, and you kind of forget that," he said.
